      "content": "The feeling of the world \"stuttering\" is often described in relation to visual processing anomalies, which can be related to how quickly and accurately our brains perceive sequential information. Some theories suggest this could be a brief disruption in visual input processing, perhaps due to fatigue or sensory overload from the rhythmic motion of the train. While there isn't a simple \"reality-stutter\" theory, these perceptual slips are well-documented neurological phenomena.",
      "source": "target",
